<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<worksheet>
  <title>EL-2 Exponential and Logarithmic Equations</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      This outcome covers exponential and logarithmic equations. You should be able to 
      solve exponential and logarithmic equations algebraically and graphically. You 
      should be able to write out complete steps to solve these types of problems 
      by hand, without the use of a calculator.
    </p>
    <p>For the quiz on this outcome you would be given 30 minutes to complete 2 problems. Here are samples 
      of the types of problems you will encounter:</p>
  </introduction>
  <objectives>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Simplifying Expressions: Simplify algebraic expressions by combining like terms and applying the 
        distributive property. Answers should be completely simplified.</p></li>
        <li><p>Basics of Graphing: Give a graph with appropriate scales and labels. The line should have the 
          correct intercepts and general behavior.</p></li>
      <li><p>Problem structure: Solution should be organized and easy to follow, with clear, complete steps 
        that follow progressively from one to the next.</p></li>
      <li><p>Mathematical Communication: Solutions should be presented in a clear and logical manner, with 
        appropriate use of mathematical notation and terminology. Equations should have at most one equal 
        sign and expressions on both sides.</p></li>
      <li><p>Find solutions to exponential equations with the same base.</p></li>
      <li><p>Find solutions to exponential equations with different bases. Leave answers as simplified fractions, 
        integers, or in terms of natural logarithms.</p></li>
      <li><p>Find solutions to logarithmic equations where all terms are logarithms.</p></li>
      <li><p>Find solutions to logarithmic equations where not all terms are logarithms.</p></li>
      <li><p>Find solutions to other exponential and logarithmic equations. Leave answers as simplified fractions, 
        integers, or in terms of natural logarithms.</p></li>
    </ul>
    </objectives>

  
  <page>
    <exercise workspace="3cm">
      <task>
        <statement><p>Solve <m>2^{3x}=36</m>.</p></statement>
        <hint><p>Rewrite the equation using the exponential-logarithmic equivalence.</p></hint>
        <answer><p><m>x=\frac{2\ln6}{3\ln2}</m></p></answer>
        <solution><p>Taking the natural logarithm of both sides gives:</p><p><m>\ln(2^{3x})=\ln(36)</m></p>
          <p><m>3x\ln2=2\ln6</m></p><p><m>x=\frac{2\ln6}{3\ln2}</m></p></solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement><p>Solve <m>\log_2(2-x)+\log_2(x)=\log_2(5)+\log_2(x-2)</m>.</p></statement>
        <hint><p>Use the properties of logarithms to combine the terms on either side of the equation.</p></hint>
        <answer><p>There is no solution.</p></answer>
        <solution><p>First, we combine the logarithms on each side:</p><p><m>\log_2((2-x)x)=\log_2(5(x-2))</m></p>
          <p>This implies:</p><p><m>(2-x)x=5(x-2)</m></p><p><m>2x-x^2=5x-10</m></p><p><m>x^2+3x-10=0</m></p>
          <p>Factoring gives:</p><p><m>(x+5)(x-2)=0</m></p><p>So <m>x=-5</m> or <m>x=2</m>. However, both values are 
            outside the domain of the original equation, so there is no solution.</p></solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement><p>Solve <m>8^{2x}-2(8^x)-8=0</m>.</p></statement>
        <hint><p>Let <m>u=8^x</m> and rewrite the equation in terms of <m>u</m>.</p></hint>
        <answer><p><m>x=\frac{2}{3}</m></p></answer>
        <solution><p>Let <m>u=8^x</m>. Then the equation becomes:</p><p><m>u^2-2u-8=0</m></p>
          <p>Factoring gives:</p><p><m>(u-4)(u+2)=0</m></p><p>So <m>u=4</m> or <m>u=-2</m>. 
            Since <m>u=8^x</m>, we have:</p><p><m>8^x=4</m> or <m>8^x=-2</m></p>
            <p>The second equation has no real solution, so we consider the first:</p><p><m>8^x=4</m></p>
            <p>Rewriting both sides in terms of base 2:</p><p><m>(2^3)^x=2^2</m></p><p><m>2^{3x}=2^2</m></p>
            <p><m>3x=2</m></p><p><m>x=\frac{2}{3}</m></p></solution>
      </task>
    </exercise>
  </page>
</worksheet>